social_posts.post_text: I was in this short sci fi film called “Black Hole” and it went on the film festival circuit over this last year and won a ton of awards. Starring @aaronmoorhead (of Moon Knight fame) and written/directed by @japars (award winning filmmaker), @black_hole_shortfilm is a movie about that ever present void in our lives that we struggle to understand but manage to live with. It’s now available to watch on @watchdust so check it out. Super grateful to have been a part of this. Watch the post credits scene. It… well… it’s something 😉

The weirdest part about these AI generated images is looking at a picture of yourself that you never took, or seeing a drawing of yourself that no one ever drew. The controversy is that the computer can’t generate these images without previously existing photos and art made by other artists to use as a foundation, but seeing how it reinterprets things in different styles is still pretty wild. Personally, I think that AI will eventually act as a tool to speed up the process or lend a hand in it, but the human mind is special because it is uniquely capable of creatively expressing new ideas in infinitely unpredictable ways. Not to mention that a big part of what makes art so captivating is the effort it takes to execute the art and then applying it in a way that makes it appealing. Art is a glimpse into the mind of a person and that is what makes it beautiful. 
The app is called @lensa.ai. It’s crazy how these pictures look straight out of a movie, video game, or cartoon.

Spider-Guys 🕷🕸🐙🎃
After seeing “No Way Home” I edited this picture together, but never posted it. Pretty excited for Spider-Verse 2 so I thought I’d share.
-
Lots of assets in this one, but that’s actually me in the Spider-Man suit and my buddy @spideyluc as Miles Morales. I wanted to recreate that awesome freeway scene from No Way Home but with Miles in it. It’s difficult to compose an action shot with so many characters and have them all facing camera. A fun challenge for sure. Matching fire lighting is no joke either. Love editing in destruction tho. So fun. Everything was edited in Adobe Photoshop and some Lightroom as well.

My take on some Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtle concept art. Cowabunga, dudes! 🐢🍕
-
I was feeling inspired by the new @tmnt trailer that dropped today and as a huge fan I wanted to share my approach to a more gritty live action/cgi turtle movie. My goal was to try and make them look somewhat like actual turtles to ground them in a darker reality to a degree, but still keep the fun proportions/silhouette that we all know and love. Lots of pieces from @adobestock to put this one together in @photoshop. Colors touched up in @lightroom.
-
Before you go off on the bandana color, in the original comics, before the OG cartoon, they all wore red. And it was a VERY gritty comic.
-
The last slide is a Leo I drew like 15 years ago or something. This is kind of a throwback to that and look at how much I’ve both progressed as an artist but also how my focus has shifted from illustration to compositing.
-
